- When adding sinusoidal functions, writing the functions in Euler's form makes sense as it allows use to easily add and subtract them.
  $V_1$ is the imaginary part of the complex number $z_1$ such that

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z_1 &= 161\left(\cos(\omega t + 1.047)+\mathrm{i} \sin(\omega t + 1.047)\right) \\[6pt]
  &= 161e^{\mathrm{i}(\omega t + 1.047)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  And $V_T$ is the imaginary part of the complex number $z_2$ such that

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z_2 &= 240\left(\cos(\omega t + 1.883)+\mathrm{i} \sin(\omega t + 1.883)\right) \\[6pt]
  &= 240e^{\mathrm{i}(\omega t + 1.883)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Given that $V_2 = V_T - V_1$, $V_2$ is the imaginary part of $z_2 - z_1$. We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z_2 - z_1 &= 240e^{\mathrm{i}(\omega t + 1.883)} - 161e^{\mathrm{i}(\omega t + 1.047)} \\[6pt]
  &= 240\left(e^{\mathrm{i}\omega t}\right)\left(e^{1.883\mathrm{i}}\right) - 161\left(e^{\mathrm{i}\omega t}\right)\left(e^{1.047\mathrm{i}}\right) \\[6pt]
  &= e^{\mathrm{i}\omega t}\left(240e^{1.883\mathrm{i}}-161e^{1.047\mathrm{i}}\right) \\[6pt]
  &= e^{\mathrm{i}\omega t}\left(178.1e^{2.618\mathrm{i}}\right) \hspace{3em}[\text{by G.D.C.}] \\[6pt]
  &= 178e^{\mathrm{i}(\omega t + 2.62)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Converting to polar form, we have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  V_2 &= \mathrm{Im}\left(178\left(\cos(\omega t + 2.62)+\mathrm{i} \sin(\omega t + 2.62)\right)\right) \\[6pt]
  &\hspace{-1em}\tcbhighmath{V_2 = 178\sin(\omega t + 2.62)}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- The phase shift of $V_1$ is $1.047$ and the phase shift of $V_2$ is $2.62$. Hence the difference is given by

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \tcbhighmath{2.62 - 1.047 \approx 1.57}
  \end{align*}
  $$

- Equating our function $\mathrm{S}(t)$ to $\mathrm{im}(z_1)+19.5$, we must have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \mathrm{im}(z_1) &= 1.85 \sin (0.52t - 1.57)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  This is the imaginary part of the complex number

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z_1 &= 1.85 \cos (0.52t - 1.57) + i\left(1.85 \sin (0.52t - 1.57)\right)
  \end{align*}
  $$

  In the required form, we have $\answer{z_1 = 1.85e^{(0.52t - 1.57)i}}$

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

  Using similar reasoning with $\mathrm{R}(t)$, we have $\answer{z_2 = 1.35e^{(0.52t - 4.7)i}}$

  $$
  \begin{aligned}			
  \tag*{\textbf{A1}}	
  \end{aligned}
  $$

- We have

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  \mathrm{D}(t) &= \mathrm{S}(t) - \mathrm{R}(t) \\[8pt]
  &= \mathrm{im}(z_1) + 19.5 - \left(\mathrm{im}(z_2) + 7.5\right) \\[8pt]
  &= \mathrm{im}(z_1) - \mathrm{im}(z_2) + 12 \\[8pt]
  &= \mathrm{im}(z_1 - z_2) + 12 \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  Let's find $z_1 - z_2$ so that we can identify the imaginary part.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  z_1 - z_2 &= 1.85e^{(0.52\hspace{0.05em}t-1.57)i} - 1.35e^{(0.52\hspace{0.05em}t-4.7)i} \\[8pt]
  &= 1.85e^{0.52ti-1.57i} - 1.35e^{0.52ti-4.7i} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[8pt]
  &= 1.85\left(e^{0.52ti}\right)\left(e^{-1.57i}\right) - 1.35\left(e^{0.52ti}\right)\left(e^{-4.7i}\right) \\[8pt]
  &= e^{0.52ti}\left(1.85e^{-1.57i}-1.35e^{-4.7i}\right) \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}
  \end{align*}
  $$

  We have now factorised the variable $t$ out of the brackets, allowing us to compute a single complex number inside the brackets.

  $$
  \begin{align*}
  &= e^{0.52ti}\left(3.199...e^{-1.565...i}\right) \hspace{3em}\text{[by G.D.C.]} \tag*{\textbf{(M1)}}\\[8pt]
  &= 3.199...e^{0.52ti-1.565...i} \\[8pt]
  &= 3.199...e^{(0.52t-1.565...)i} \\[8pt]
  z_1 - z_2 &= 3.20e^{(0.52t-1.57)i} \,\text{(3 s.f.)} \tag*{\textbf{(A1)}}
  \end{align*}
